# File Structure Convention

Canonical layout for everything under `src/`. Read before adding any file. The route-island skill ([`agent-os/skills/route-island/SKILL.md`](../skills/route-island/SKILL.md)) implements these rules step-by-step; this is the contract.

## The pages rule in five lines

1. **`src/pages/` mirrors the URL tree 1:1.** `/login` ‚Üí `pages/login/`; `/organization/acme/dashboard` ‚Üí `pages/organization/$organizationSlug/dashboard/`. Children nest **directly** (no `sub-pages/` bucket); dynamic segments are `$param` folders with full-word names. One exception: `/` is a pure resolver route (redirect only, no island).
2. **Every page folder maintains the same 4 files** ‚Äî `<page>.route.tsx`, `<page>.manifest.ts`, `<Page>Page.tsx` (or `<Page>Layout.tsx`), `<PAGE>.OVERVIEW.md` ‚Äî plus 2 registrations: `src/app/routes/routeTree.tsx` and `docs/reference/routes-and-ui.md`. `$param` folders derive their prefix mechanically (strip `$`, kebab-case).
3. **Page shells live in `shared/layouts/`** ‚Äî `AuthLayout` via the pathless `auth-shell` route; `AppLayout` via the `pages/organization/$organizationSlug/` layout island (the org guard boundary). No grouping directories under `pages/`.
4. **Promotion ladder:** one page ‚Üí inside that page; a page + its OWN nested children ‚Üí that page's `shared/` (family-shared, e.g. `pages/organization/$organizationSlug/shared/`); pages from different families or any `src/shared` component ‚Üí root `src/shared/` (`shared/api/auth-api.ts`, `shared/tenancy/`, ‚Ä¶).
5. **Settings is a global hash modal, not a route space** ‚Äî `#settings/<scope>/<section>` (see "Settings hash modal" below). Full routing/tenancy spec: `docs/reference/routing-and-tenancy.md`.

## Top-Level Layout

```
tests/                                  At project root: ci/, cross-browser/, e2e/, factories/, fixtures/, performance/, security/, utils/
src/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ app/                                Application shell: route tree, guards, providers, error boundaries
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ core/                               Framework-agnostic services
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ pages/                              Page-first feature directories (each = a frontend route)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ shared/                             Cross-page reusables: components, forms, hooks, layouts, store
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ lib/                                Pure utilities (no side effects)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ App.tsx
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ main.tsx
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.css
```

**`src/core/`** is the irreducible platform kernel ‚Äî only framework-agnostic, app-state-free services: `http/`, `rbac/`, `security/`, `config/`, `data-provider/`, `resources/`, `types/`, `version/`. **Anything app-layout-y, React-Provider-y, or app-state-dependent lives outside `core/`:**
- App-shell bootstrap (Sentry init, web-vitals, PostHog setup) ‚Üí **`src/app/`** (`app/analytics/`, `app/observability/`)
- Runtime infrastructure used by every layer (auth token + service, errors handling) ‚Üí **`src/shared/`** (`shared/auth/`, `shared/errors/`)
- Zustand client state ‚Üí **`src/shared/store/<X>Store/`** (folder-per-unit) ‚Äî all 7 stores including `useAuthStore` and `useOrganizationStore`
- Cross-page API helpers ‚Üí **`src/shared/api/`** (`auth-*`, `organization-*`)
- Organization/tenancy runtime (URL-driven context, membership, `/` resolver, my-organizations) ‚Üí **`src/shared/tenancy/`**

## Naming ‚Äî three categories

### 1. Role files ‚Äî page-prefixed, lowercase-dotted

One per page. The prefix makes them globally unique ‚Üí AI agents, grep, and IDE quick-open all resolve without ambiguity.

| File | Required? | Purpose |
|------|-----------|---------|
| `<page>.route.tsx` | ‚úì | Lazy boundary (`Component` only; optional `ErrorBoundary` if wired in routeTree) |
| `<page>.manifest.ts` | ‚úì | Manifest: `path`, `title`, `testId`, `permission`, `kind`, `children` |
| `<page>.contracts.ts` | optional | Zod schemas + inferred TS types |
| `<page>.api.ts` | optional | Fetcher functions for this page |
| `<page>.search.ts` | optional | URL search-param schema (TanStack Router `validateSearch`) |
| `<page>.fixtures.ts` | optional | Mock generators (marked `REPLACE_WITH_API`) |
| `<page>.constants.ts` | optional | Page-scoped constants |
| `<page>.resource.ts` | resource pages only | Resource manifest (endpoint, schema, permissions) |

### 2. Entry doc ‚Äî `<PAGE>.OVERVIEW.md` (UPPER_SNAKE name ¬∑ dotted role)

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `<PAGE>.OVERVIEW.md` | AI/human entry doc ‚Äî first file an agent reads on this island. Name = UPPERCASE directory name with `-` ‚Üí `_`; the dot separates name from role, mirroring the `<page>.route.tsx` grammar (`pages/login/` ‚Üí `LOGIN.OVERVIEW.md`). Every overview filename is globally unique (grep/quick-open/agent file-matching never collide) while staying visibly a doc, like `README.md`. Applies outside `pages/` too: `shared/api/API.OVERVIEW.md`, `shared/auth/AUTH.OVERVIEW.md`, `app/guards/GUARDS.OVERVIEW.md`. |

### 3. UI files ‚Äî PascalCase

| File | When |
|------|------|
| `<Page>Page.tsx` | Top-level UI; manifest `kind: 'leaf'` |
| `<Page>Layout.tsx` | Top-level UI; manifest `kind: 'layout'` (mounts `<Outlet />`) |
| Sub-units in `components/`, `forms/`, `hooks/`, `dialogs/`, `store/` | See "Folder-per-unit" below |

## Folder-per-unit (components, forms, hooks, dialogs, store)

Every component / form / hook / dialog / store lives in its own folder with three files:

```
<Name>/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ <Name>.tsx              source (or .ts for hooks/store)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ <Name>.test.tsx         test (or .ts)
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.ts                export { <Name> } from './<Name>.tsx';
```

Apply to:
- `components/<Name>/`
- `forms/<Name>Form/`
- `hooks/use<Name>/`
- `dialogs/<Name>Dialog/`
- `store/use<X>Store/`

**Sub-unit names are not page-prefixed** ‚Äî the path already provides context:
- ‚úì `pages/dashboard/components/ActivityFeed/`
- ‚úó `pages/dashboard/components/DashboardActivityFeed/`

**Exception ‚Äî shadcn primitives stay flat.** `src/shared/components/ui/` keeps the shadcn convention (`button.tsx`, `card.tsx`, etc.) ‚Äî no folder-per-unit.

**Exception ‚Äî cohesive flat groups.** A multi-file component group that only makes sense as a set keeps flat files inside its parent folder: the `SettingsModal` panel groups (`account/`, `organization/`). Tests colocate beside the group's logic files. Everything else follows folder-per-unit (the former `data-table/` flat group is now four folder-per-unit components: `DataTable/`, `DataTableColumnHeader/`, `DataTablePagination/`, `DataTableToolbar/`).

## Page Naming (directory)

| Pattern | Use for | Example |
|---------|---------|---------|
| **Plural noun** | Collection / list view | `pages/organizations/` ‚Üí `/organizations` |
| **Singular noun** | Single resource (current context) | `pages/organization/` ‚Üí `/organization` (user's current org) |
| **kebab-case verb-noun** | Action / workflow | `pages/create-organization/` ‚Üí `/create-organization` |
| **kebab-case noun** | Multi-word concept | `pages/accept-invite/` ‚Üí `/accept-invite` |

Page directory names are **lowercase kebab-case**. Child route folders follow the same rules and nest directly (`organization/$organizationSlug/api-keys/`); dynamic segments are `$param` folders with full-word param names (`$organizationSlug/`, `$patientId/` ‚Äî never `$orgId`).

**Sanctioned exception:** `pages/organization/` is singular yet serves the picker (a collection view) at `/organization` ‚Äî it doubles as the `$organizationSlug/` parent, so the URL spec (`routing-and-tenancy.md` ¬ß2) wins over the plural-for-collections naming row.

**Sanctioned exception ‚Äî param-only leaf:** when a route's final segment is a
`$param` and the parent segment has **no page of its own** (nothing renders at the
parent URL), the island stays flat and its manifest carries the param in `path` ‚Äî
`pages/accept-invite/` owns `/accept-invite/$invitationId` directly; an empty
`$invitationId/` folder under a page-less parent would add a directory with no
route, manifest, or UI of its own. The `$param` folder rule applies when the parent
segment is itself a page (`organization/$organizationSlug/`).

## Two page shapes ‚Äî custom and resource

